et threat allowed policymakers in Washington to more aggressively pursue trade interests that conflicted with those of China. Given this international context, this book aims to discern how Congress reconciled competing Sino-U.S. interests in a post-Cold War era, when external threats no longer dictated an apparent hierarchy that favored China over the Soviet Union.This work will be of interest to students and scholars of US foreign policy, China Studies and international relations in general"--cProvided by publisher.  a16 4310aUnited States.bCongress. 0aUnited StatesxForeign relationszChina. 0aChinaxForeign relationszUnited States. 0aUnited StatesxForeign relationsy1989- 0aRoutledge studies in US foreign policy.  aE 183.8 C5 G324 2015c1hUAHS-Bi0162035200698  aE 183.8 C5 G324 2015wLCc1i0162035204336lON_SHELFmUAAUGp$150.00rYsYtBOOKu12/18/2014  aE 183.8 C5 G324 2015wLCc1i0162035200698lON_SHELFmUAHSSp$150.00rYsYtBOOKu12/18/201401ahttp://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n2014021481